./test_fail2ban.sh
Task 2: Implement Basic Firewall Rules in UFW
Subtask 2.1: Understanding UFW
UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall) is a user-friendly front-end for managing iptables firewall rules in Ubuntu. It provides a simple command-line interface for creating firewall rules without needing to learn complex iptables syntax.

Key concepts:

Default policies: What to do with traffic that doesn't match any rules
Allow rules: Permit specific traffic
Deny rules: Block specific traffic
Port-based rules: Control access to specific services
Application profiles: Pre-defined rules for common applications
Subtask 2.2: Check UFW Status and Enable It
Check the current status of UFW:

sudo ufw status
If UFW is inactive, enable it:

sudo ufw enable
Important: When enabling UFW, you might see a warning about disrupting SSH connections. Type 'y' to proceed, as we'll configure SSH access in the next steps.

Subtask 2.3: Configure Default Policies
Set up secure default policies:

# Deny all incoming traffic by default
sudo ufw default deny incoming

# Allow all outgoing traffic by default
sudo ufw default allow outgoing
Verify the default policies:

sudo ufw status verbose
Subtask 2.4: Allow Essential Services
Allow SSH access (critical for remote management):

sudo ufw allow ssh
Or specify the port number explicitly:

sudo ufw allow 22/tcp
Allow HTTP and HTTPS traffic (for web services):

sudo ufw allow http
sudo ufw allow https
Or using port numbers:

sudo ufw allow 80/tcp
sudo ufw allow 443/tcp
Subtask 2.5: Create Specific Rules
Allow access from a specific IP address:

sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.100
Allow a specific port from a specific IP:

sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.100 to any port 3306
Allow a range of ports:

sudo ufw allow 8000:8010/tcp
Deny access from a specific IP:

sudo ufw deny from 203.0.113.100
Subtask 2.6: View and Manage Rules
List all rules with numbers:

sudo ufw status numbered
Delete a specific rule by number (replace X with the rule number):

sudo ufw delete X
Reset all rules (use with caution):

sudo ufw --force reset
