Subtask 3.2: Create Automated Security Checks
Create a comprehensive security check script:

nano security_check.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Comprehensive Security Check ==="
echo "Timestamp: $(date)"
echo ""

# Check if Fail2Ban is running
echo "1. Checking Fail2Ban Service:"
if systemctl is-active --quiet fail2ban; then
    echo "   ✓ Fail2Ban is running"
    echo "   Active jails: $(sudo fail2ban-client status | grep "Jail list" | cut -d: -f2 | tr -d ' ')"
else
    echo "   ✗ Fail2Ban is not running"
fi
echo ""

# Check if UFW is enabled
echo "2. Checking UFW Status:"
ufw_status=$(sudo ufw status | head -1)
if [[ $ufw_status == *"active"* ]]; then
    echo "   ✓ UFW is active"
    rule_count=$(sudo ufw status numbered | grep -c "^\[")
    echo "   Active rules: $rule_count"
else
    echo "   ✗ UFW is inactive"
fi
echo ""

# Check for recent security events
echo "3. Recent Security Events:"
failed_logins=$(sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log | tail -5 | wc -l)
echo "   Recent failed login attempts: $failed_logins"

# Check open ports
echo ""
echo "4. Open Network Ports:"
netstat -tuln | grep LISTEN | awk '{print $4}' | sort | uniq
echo ""

# Check system updates
echo "5. System Update Status:"
updates_available=$(apt list --upgradable 2>/dev/null | grep -c upgradable)
echo "   Available updates: $updates_available"
echo ""

echo "=== Security Check Complete ==="
Make the script executable and run it:

chmod +x security_check.sh
./security_check.sh
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Fail2Ban Not Starting
If Fail2Ban fails to start, check the configuration:

sudo fail2ban-client -t
Check the service logs:

sudo journalctl -u fail2ban -f
Issue 2: UFW Blocking Legitimate Traffic
If you accidentally block yourself out, you can disable UFW from the console:

sudo ufw disable
Then reconfigure your rules and re-enable it.

Issue 3: Log Files Not Found
Ensure log files exist and have proper permissions:

sudo ls -la /var/log/auth.log
sudo ls -la /var/log/ufw.log
Issue 4: Testing Connectivity
Use these commands to test network connectivity:

# Test specific ports
nc -zv localhost 22
nc -zv localhost 80

# Check listening services
sudo ss -tlnp
Best Practices and Security Considerations
Regular Monitoring: Check security logs daily
Update Rules: Review and update firewall rules monthly
Backup Configurations: Keep backups of your security configurations
Test Changes: Always test firewall changes in a safe environment first
Document Rules: Maintain documentation of why each rule exists
Monitor Performance: Ensure security tools don't impact system performance significantly
